 regain/develop their love for education.I also understand that we the deaf community need to learn english and integrate with the hearing community but we can do this with the use of bsl, so we can continue the deaf culture whilst educating the hearing about the deaf culture and bsl. I feel that mary hare is the right place for me as it uses a oral approach in lessons &amp; have specialist teachers of the deaf,so interactive white boards are used as a visual learning tool. MH will also mean thati can combine a levels with a subsidary btec in health and social care,i would be apprenhensive about embarking down the a level route at mainstream. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="954" language="en" documentId="4995" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://nigallant.blogspot.co.uk/2012/07/deaf-education-vs-mainstream-education.html" topic="mainstreaming" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4995" notes="" title="Deaf Education vs. Mainstream Education - Kathryn"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="954"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>